.he CIRCUIT CONSTRUCTION SYSTEM

PURPOSE AND COMPONENTS

.in +5
The circuit contruction system consists of a series of utilities, which will
accomplish the following:

.lm +5
.rm -5
1. Convert a circuit description from ascii format to hierarchical netlist.

2. Convert from a grapical database onto netlist.

3. Convert to or from an alternate format netlist to or from the system
netlist.

4. Convert a pattern generation and simulation control file to the system
control file format.

5. Perform high-speed simulation and faulting.

6. Convert simulation results to graphic printout.

.lm -5
.rm + 5
.in +5
These actions are accomplished by the following utilities:

.lm +5
.rm -5
cas - Circuit assembler. Converts an ascii source file to a netlist.

cpg - Circuit pattern generator. Converts an ascii pattern generation
specification to a set file.

sim - Circuit simulator. Simulates a given circuit.

trc - Trace convertion utility. Converts output trace files to ascii
graphic output files.

.lm -5
.rm +5
.in +5
The following file types are used:

.lm +5
.rm -5
file.ckt - Contains an ascii circuit source.

file.ctl - Contains ascii pattern generator statements.

file.fmt - Contains ascii trace format statements.

file.net - The binary netlist.

file.dic - The name dictionary for the netlist.

file.set - The binary pattern generation file.

file.trc - The binary trace output file.

file.lst - The list output of the trace utility.

.lm -5
.rm +5

FORMAT OF ASCII CIRCUIT SOURCE

.in +5
The circuit source is free format. This means that the end of a line is
equivalent to a space, and circuit statements may cross lines without
"continuation" marks. The assembly consists of a series of "cells", which
have "headers" and "bodys". The header specifies all connections to and
from the circuitry contained within a cell, and the body specifies all
circuitry that constructs the cell. Cells are not nested, and appear
consequtively. Cells may include other cells by reference, but only if
they have already appeared. The source, then, typically consists of the
primitive cells listed first, up until the last cell, which is the most
complex cell, and is in fact considered to be the final circuit for
practical purposes. A special cell header without a body serves to indicate
that the actual cell body lies in a cell library (and "external" cell).
The following is a typical source file:

.lm +5
.rm -5
{

Non-inverting buffer

}

cell inv: input, output, vdd, vss;

   peif: vdd, input, output, vdd, 84u, 3u;
   neif: vss, input, output, vss, 49u, 3u

endcell;

cell buff: input, output, vdd, vss;

   inv: input, n1, vdd, vss;
   inv: n1, output, vdd, vss

endcell


.lm -5
.rm +5
.in +5
This example consists of only two cells, and constructs a non-inverting
buffer. The buffer is actually made up of two back to back inverters, of
which each is it's own cell. The first cell defines the inverter using
individual transistors, and the second uses those to construct a buffer.
Each transistor is a "device", and such devices are predeclared. The format
of a device call is the same as a cell call however, and the user may
think of a device as being a predefined cell. In fact, cases may arise when
a special purpose device is constructed out of primitive devices.

CELL HEADER

.in +5
This is of the form:

.lm +5
.rm -5
cell name: parameter1, parameter2, ... parameter n;

.lm -5
.rm +5
.in +5
Each parameter represents a value or node to be passed into the cell.
Whether or not the parameter is a node or a numeric value is determined
by how the node is used in the cell. If it appears as a node parameter
to a device, it is a node. If it appears, say, as a width or length parameter,
it is numeric.
.in +5
It is possible for a cell to have NO parameters. In this case, the list
of parameters, and the ":" after the cell name are omitted.
.in +5
Note that unless told not to, the assembler will flag warnings about
parameters that are not used within the body of a cell.

CELL BODY

.in +5
The cell body consists of a sequence of statements separated by ";", and
terminated by the "endcell" statement. These can be any of device statements
or cell references. Attempts to reference the current cell (a recursive
reference) will fail, and generate a "cell not found" error message. This
is because a cell is not considered to be defined until it's end.
Note that unless told not to, the assembler will flag warnings about nodes
appearing in the body of a block that have no apparent low impedence path.
This would mean nodes that only have a transistor gate, or one end of a
capacitor attached. Nodes that appear as parameters are an exception to the
rule, as their path is not complete until the cell is actually used.
This may cause confusion, as an error will appear even when a node appears
as a parameter to a another cell. The meaning is that no low impedence paths
exist in that cell.
Note that only the nodes defined as parameters may provide external access
for the circuit. In particular, this strict rule means that the header
of each cell must provide for power connections.

NODE FORMAT

A node is formed of a series of ascii characters, up to approximately 200
characters in length (the user should not count on more than 40 characters
of significance to be retained). The basic node name consists of one of
the characters 'a'..'z' or '_' followed by any of 'a'..'z', '_', or '0'..'9'
(that is, a node label MAY NOT begin with a digit). Allowed at the end is
an "index specification", of the form name[num]. The "num" is an integer
indicating which node of a vector of nodes is indicated. Other than checking
for proper format, the simple form of index is only checked. It will otherwise
appear as if the "[" and "]" symbols were just ordinary characters in the
node name. The exception is the "range" specification, of the form name[x:y].
Whenever this appears, it will automatically be expanded into a series of
indexed nodes. This is done by creating a node for each value between x and
y inclusive. Examples:

.lm +5
.rm -5
a[0:3] -> a[0], a[1], a[2], a[3]

d[3:2] -> d[3], d[2]

.lm -5
.rm +5
.in +5
Note that the nodes will appear in the same order as the values x and y
appear. It is quite another matter as to what results from this specification.
Whatever device or cell it appears in must have node parameter "slots" to
handle the generated nodes. The total number of parameters must still match.
Note that no errors or warnings are generated about name mismatches. The
specification:

.in +5
inv: a[0:3]

.in +5
Would have satisfied the inverter cell specified above. Calling a cell
with parameters declared as a[0:3] as a[3:0] would connect the bits backwards
without complaint.

NUMERIC FORMAT

The format of all numbers is in floating point with optional exponent, as
"ddd.dddexx". You may also use the following to stand in for
exponents:

.lm +5
.rm -5
f   (femto) 10e-15
p   (pico)  10e-12
n   (nano)  10e-9
u   (micro) 10e-6
m   (mili)  10e-3
k   (kili)  10e+3
meg (mega)  10e+6
g   (giga)  10e+9
t   (tera)  10e+12
mil         25.4*10e-6

.lm -5
.rm +5
You may also use the mathematical operators +, -, *, /, and parenthities
to group expressions.

BASIC DEVICES

The basic devices are built in to the assembler, and have a predefined calling
format. The assembler will handle many devices common in electronics, but
just because the assembler will generate them doesn't nessaryly mean that
the resulting net can be simulated. Devices that are not represented here can
be constructed two ways. First, a special device can be specified as the
combination of several "ideal" devices. In this way, interlead capacitences,
etc., can be modeled by adding devices as done in standard electronic
analisis. Second, a device can be represented by an external cell, and that
cell left unresolved. A special purpose simulator can then implement it's
own device model.

neif: source, gate, drain, substrate, width, length - N channel, enhancement
mode, insulated gate, field effect transistor. Insulated gate also covers
MOSFET and silicon gate transistors.

peif: source, gate, drain, substrate, width, length - P channel, enhancement
mode, insulated gate FET.

wneif: source gate, drain, substrate, width, length - This is the same as
"neif", except that it indicates a special weak drive strength mode to the
simulator.

wpeif: source, gate, drain, substrate, width, length - Same as peif with
weak drive strength.

bjnpn: collector, base, emitter - A bipolar NPN transistor.

bjpnp: collector, base, emitter - A bipolar PNP transistor.

res: terminal a, terminal b, ohms - An ideal resistor.

cap: terminal a (also positive terminal), terminal b (also negative terminal),
farads - An ideal capacitor.

ind: terminal a, terminal b, henrys - An ideal inductor.
